04500nam a22005175i 9780226117607DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20212014ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2013027389  a9780226117607  a(DE-B1597)568082  a(OCoLC)1233040889  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aB995.F744bA3 2014 4aB995.F744bA3 2014 7aBIO0000002bisacsh04a362.8830921 aFreedman, Karyn L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOne Hour in Paris :bA True Story of Rape and Recovery /cKaryn L. Freedman. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrologue -- t1: Paris, August 1, 1990 -- t2: What Happened Next -- t3: Live In It -- t4: Africa, 2008 -- t5: Paris, Revisited -- tAcknowledgments -- tFurther Reading0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this powerful memoir, philosopher Karyn L. Freedman travels back to a Paris night in 1990 when she was twenty-two and, in one violent hour, her life was changed forever by a brutal rape. One Hour in Paris takes the reader on a harrowing yet inspirational journey through suffering and recovery both personal and global. We follow Freedman from an apartment in Paris to a French courtroom, then from a trauma center in Toronto to a rape clinic in Africa. At a time when as many as one in three women in the world have been victims of sexual assault and when many women are still ashamed to come forward, Freedman’s book is a moving and essential look at how survivors cope and persevere. At once deeply intimate and terrifyingly universal, One Hour in Paris weaves together Freedman’s personal experience with the latest philosophical, neuroscientific, and psychological insights on what it means to live in a body that has been traumatized. Using her background as a philosopher, she looks at the history of psychological trauma and draws on recent theories of posttraumatic stress disorder and neuroplasticity to show how recovery from horrific experiences is possible. Through frank discussions of sex and intimacy, she explores the consequences of sexual violence for love and relationships, and she illustrates the steep personal cost of sexual violence and the obstacles faced by individual survivors in its aftermath. Freedman’s book is an urgent call to face this fundamental social problem head-on, arguing that we cannot continue to ignore the fact that sexual violence against women is rooted in gender inequalities that exist worldwide—and must be addressed. One Hour in Paris is essential reading for survivors of sexual violence as well as an invaluable resource for therapists, mental health professionals, and family members and friends of victims.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aRape victimsvBiography. 0aWomen philosopherszCanadavBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh  arape, trauma, sexual assault, healing, memoir, trial, legal system, paris, gender, womens issues, toronto, canada, france, europe, africa, survivor, victim, posttraumatic stress disorder, ptsd, neuroplasticity, recovery, sex, intimacy, violence, love, relationships, aftermath, coping, biography, autobiography, feminism, nonfiction, women philosophers, philosophy, psychology, crime, flashbacks, trust, travel.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226117607423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226117607/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles